### Snippet 5: Performance Question

1. Use ListView.builder or slivers.
   This builds only visible rows instead of creating the whole transaction widget list at once. It is most useful when the list can grow beyond a small static set.

2. Paginate data.
   Loading the first page quickly improves perceived speed, and later pages can be fetched as the user scrolls. This also limits memory usage.

3. Optimize images.
   Images should have fixed dimensions, fallbacks, decode sizing, and caching. This avoids layout shifts, reduces memory pressure.

4. Scope widget rebuilds.
   Use extracted row widgets, `const` constructors, `buildWhen`, or `BlocSelector` so updating paging/loading state does not rebuild unrelated parts of the screen.

5. Manage memory and lifecycle.
   Dispose controllers/listeners, avoid retaining duplicate large lists.
